The Scorching Sands are a superheated dune-sea and ember-basin complex in the east-southeastern desert corridor.
Four micro-zones: Ember Dunes (tall red-gold ridges trapping heat overnight), Kiln Basins (blackened depressions with permanent breath-burn hazards from ritual firing), Cinder Channels (former distributary cuts used as convoy lanes, wind-sheltered but ambush-prone), and Ashglass Rims (fused sand/slag belts transitioning toward the Saltglass Reach's Glasswind Belts).
Originally a fraud-resistant certification district of the Salt Ledger Kingdoms. Kiln houses fired sun-baked verification clay that changed color irreversibly when tampered with.
The Burn Ledger is a semi-buried audit complex recording kiln batches, water allotments, and passage fees in one integrated archive.
The Scorch Clause is a contract rider still invoked by merchants: supplemental water for cargo in transit, mandatory heat-certification of seals, liability segmented by route. It anticipated maritime-style risk law before the Saltglass Reach formalized it.
Three factions hold ground. Ember Wardens descend from route inspectors and kiln officers, maintaining shade stations under the credo "No crossing without measure." Ashbound Reavers are convoy raiders who strike where water discipline breaks down. The Cauterist Synod treats heat as purgative truth, brands false seals as heresy, and stages trial-by-sun rites at abandoned kiln mouths.
Three daily heat phases govern survival: Hard Glare (midday surface burns, rapid dehydration), Breathfire (late afternoon trapped basin heat causing inhalation damage), False Mercy (nighttime residual ground heat masked by apparent cooling).
The system collapsed when the Iseth dried. Kiln houses lost their water supply; certification continued as empty ritual.
Common sayings: "Shade is borrowed law." "The sun sees the false seal first."

