Midgaard's Bureau of Eastern Routes classifies the Scorching Sands as a collapsed certification district of administrative interest.
The sun-fired verification clay and Burn Ledger audit complex are recognized as a parallel administrative tradition to Midgaard's own Oath of the Kept Record. The Sands' integrated approach (cargo, water, fees in one archive) exceeded Midgaard's ledger architecture in elegance.
The Scorch Clause anticipated maritime-style risk segmentation generations before the Saltglass Reach formalized it. A translated copy is maintained in standards reference, eastern drawer, second shelf.
The Ember Wardens' credo "No crossing without measure" is classified as a parallel to Midgaard's Oath of the Counted Step.
The system failed not by design but by supply chain collapse. When the Iseth dried, certification lost its resource base. The Burn Ledger recorded transactions for goods that no longer moved through defunct routes. Forms persisted; substance evaporated.
Ashbound Reavers are logistics predators exploiting the gap between surviving procedure and collapsed supply. The Cauterist Synod transformed quality control into theology, a corruption Midgaard's Violet Compact-era clerks recognize.
The three heat phases (Hard Glare, Breathfire, False Mercy) are formally incorporated into Midgaard's eastern convoy patrol manuals.
The Continuity faction cites the Sands as proof good systems need stable resources. The Reckoning faction cites them as proof perfect records do not prevent institutional death.

