Mafdet's Ledger Houses regard the Scorching Sands as an ancestral source of their verification systems. The kiln houses' sun-fired clay that changed color when tampered with is studied like old hull designs -- not as curiosity but as ancestral technology.
The principle matches Mafdet's Dual-Attestation Protocol: a document that cannot be altered without visible evidence is the foundation of honest commerce.
The Burn Ledger is the closest inland equivalent to the Ledger House system. One building, multiple verification streams, cross-referenced records. It solved the same core problem: how to certify cargo when the carrier has every incentive to lie.
The Scorch Clause echoes directly in Mafdet's maritime contracts. Supplemental allocation, mandatory material certification, route-segmented liability -- these are operating procedures for Mafdet, not abstractions. Shoreward Assessors converting inland contracts to maritime law find the Scorch Clause's structure visible in every conversion table.
The Ember Wardens maintaining shade stations under "No crossing without measure" are kin to Mafdet's Harbor Wardens. Measurement before movement. Attestation before passage.
Ashbound Reavers disrupt supply chains. The Sand-Sea Carters' Guild factors Reaver losses into corridor pricing, effectively a tax on lawlessness that raises costs at Mafdet's docks.
The Cauterist Synod perverts the verification principle. The Shrine of the First Claw demands swift justice for oath-breakers, but justice requires a living authority accountable for the verdict. Fire is not an authority. Fire does not sign its name.
The Sands are where Mafdet's systems came from. The kiln houses fired the first tamper-proof seals. The Burn Ledger kept the first integrated manifests. Mafdet inherited their rigor and must not inherit their collapse.
